    &lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Click on the “Add scheduled action” button and create an action with settings similar to the screenshot below. This will be the action that tells AWS when you want your instance to start running. The cron schedule of &lt;code class=&quot;language-text&quot;&gt;0 15 * * *&lt;/code&gt; will make this action start at 15:00 UTC everyday. Note that you can leave the “End time” field empty. Click the “Save” button when you’re finished.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
  &lt;span
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-wrapper&quot;
    style=&quot;position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 690px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;span
      class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-background-image&quot;
      style=&quot;padding-bottom: 73.06226175349428%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;&quot;
    &gt;
      &lt;img
        class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-image&quot;
        style=&quot;width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;&quot;
        alt=&quot;Scheduled Action&quot;
        title=&quot;&quot;
        src=&quot;/static/scheduled-action-1b4021ae63537c1e4f780817319a04d1-ad1f0.png&quot;
        srcset=&quot;/static/scheduled-action-1b4021ae63537c1e4f780817319a04d1-71707.png 173w,
/static/scheduled-action-1b4021ae63537c1e4f780817319a04d1-14127.png 345w,
/static/scheduled-action-1b4021ae63537c1e4f780817319a04d1-ad1f0.png 690w,
/static/scheduled-action-1b4021ae63537c1e4f780817319a04d1-6758f.png 1035w,
/static/scheduled-action-1b4021ae63537c1e4f780817319a04d1-c0f94.png 1380w,
/static/scheduled-action-1b4021ae63537c1e4f780817319a04d1-aa1b5.png 1574w&quot;
        sizes=&quot;(max-width: 690px) 100vw, 690px&quot;
      /&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Create another Scheduled Action with similar settings to create an action that tells AWS when you want your instance to &lt;em&gt;stop&lt;/em&gt; running. I changed the “Name” of the action to “InvokeSleep”, min and max instances to zero, and “Recurrence” to &lt;code class=&quot;language-text&quot;&gt;0 16 * * *&lt;/code&gt; so that the instance is running one hour per day (15:00 to 16:00 UTC).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once you’re happy with your scheduled actions, click on the “Apply” button and these changes should take into effect! Note that you’ll need to wait for the “Next occurrence” of these actions to notice any differences. You can check how many instances are running by looking at the “Current status” field under the Time-based Scaling section. Your environment health will show “No data” when no instances are running.&lt;/p&gt;
